## 3.2 Retrieving data for TensorFlow/Keras models

TensorFlow supports several methods for loading datasets:  
the `tf.data` API, Keras DataGenerators, and the TensorFlow-Datasets (TFDS)
package. The right choice depends on dataset size and required preprocessing.

---

### 3.2.1 tf.data API

The `tf.data` API provides a highly scalable and efficient input pipeline. It
supports parallel reading, caching, shuffling, mapping transformations,
batching, and prefetching—making it ideal for large datasets.

#### Figure 3.7 — End-to-end tf.data pipeline
<p align='left'><img src='./figure/figure3.7.png' width='60%'></p>

---

### 3.2.2 Keras DataGenerators

Keras DataGenerators are useful for loading images directly from directories.
They support on-the-fly data augmentation and allow streaming of data that
does not fit entirely into memory.

---

### 3.2.3 tensorflow-datasets (TFDS)

TFDS provides standardized, ready-to-use datasets with automatic downloading,
validation, and built-in train/test splits. It is the fastest way to load common
benchmark datasets.

---

## Summary

Chapter 3 introduces the three Keras model-building APIs—Sequential,
Functional, and Sub-classing—and the three main TensorFlow data-loading
methods: `tf.data`, DataGenerators, and TFDS. Together, these tools form a
flexible, scalable pipeline for deep learning workflows in TensorFlow 2.
